<sect2 id="python-fu-foggify">
  <title>Fog</title>

  <indexterm>
    <primary>Filters</primary>
    <secondary>Render</secondary>
    <tertiary>Fog</tertiary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm><primary>Fog</primary></indexterm>

  <sect3>
    <title>Overview</title>

    <figure>
      <title>Example for the <quote>Fog</quote> filter</title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="JPG"
            fileref="images/filters/examples/taj_orig.jpg" />
        </imageobject>
        <caption>
          <para>Original image</para>
        </caption>
      </mediaobject>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="JPG"
            fileref="images/filters/examples/decor/taj-fog.jpg" />
        </imageobject>
        <caption>
          <para><quote>Fog</quote> applied</para>
        </caption>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>

    <para>
      This filter adds a new layer with some clouds to the image that look
      like fog or smoke. The clouds are created with the
      <link linkend="gimp-filter-plasma">Plasma</link> texture.
    </para>
  </sect3>


  <sect3>
    <title>Activating the Filter</title>
    <para>
      This filter is found in the main menu under
      <menuchoice>
        <guimenu>Filters</guimenu>
        <guisubmenu>Decor</guisubmenu>
        <guimenuitem>Fogâ€¦</guimenuitem>
      </menuchoice>.
    </para>
  </sect3>

  <sect3>
    <title>Options</title>
    <figure>
      <title><quote>Fog</quote> options</title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="PNG"
            fileref="images/filters/decor/fog-dialog.png" />
        </imageobject>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>

    <variablelist>
      <para>
        Among the few filter options, only <quote>Turbulence</quote> is
        somewhat important, because you can't change it later and have to undo
        and repeat the filter if the result doesn't fit your desire.
      </para>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Layer name</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The name of the layer. You can change it later in the
            <link linkend="gimp-layer-attributes">Layers Dialog</link>.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Fog color</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            Defaults to some kind of sandy brown (240, 180, 70). Click on the
            color button to change this if you think that is not the natural
            color of fog.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Turbulence</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This is actually the Turbulence option of the
            <link linkend="gimp-filter-plasma">Plasma</link> filter: it controls
            the complexity of the clouds, from soft (low values) to hard (high
            values).
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Opacity</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The opacity of the layer. You can change it later in the <link
            linkend="gimp-layer-dialog-opacity-scale">Layers Dialog</link>.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect3>
</sect2>
